WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:15.436 --> 00:00:18.525
﻿Plasma Youth Sports Games
with Unsuccess of the champion,

00:00:18.669 --> 00:00:21.150
would like to thank Slaven Bilić
for stepping in as the host.

00:00:21.287 --> 00:00:24.478
Bilić is one of the first sponsors,
ambassador and is our biggest promoter.

00:00:24.642 --> 00:00:27.877
He used his life and sports experience
in order to prepare high-quality content

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:29.964
with his guests for all generations.
Thanks, Nane!

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:32.180
Let's go to Belgrade.

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:58.220
There are several reasons.
The first is that the show is excellent.

00:01:58.940 --> 00:02:04.100
The show is beneficial for children.
All of this was initiated by Zdrave.

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:08.820
It's part of the Youth Sports Games.
The show is great for children.

00:02:09.980 --> 00:02:16.140
As a form of literature.
It’s good for the fans.

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:20.780
It’s good for athletes.
It's also useful for me as a coach.

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:26.580
It's good for children and parents
so that they can see what a top player

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:33.340
or official has to go through
in their development.

00:02:34.060 --> 00:02:42.860
And that there are rare cases where
everything goes according to plan.

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:47.740
Painlessly, without difficulty
and problems.

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:52.540
We can only confirm that the old
Latin proverb per aspera ad astra

00:02:52.780 --> 00:03:00.719
(through hardship to the stars) isn't
just a myth or a legend but the truth.

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:07.340
In principle, the rule applies that
the more successful a person is,

00:03:07.620 --> 00:03:09.899
the more defeats they have.

00:03:10.127 --> 00:03:18.602
Difficulties aren't pleasant, but they're
the ones that, if you get out of them,

00:03:19.500 --> 00:03:24.500
that forge greats and champions.
All of them.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:34.020
Zdrave is great friend of mine and he
asked me to do few shows which

00:03:34.700 --> 00:03:40.660
he calls specials and it was
hard for me to refuse him.

00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:44.060
The third reason is that I have time.

00:03:44.300 --> 00:03:48.620
The fourth reason is that
this is important to me,

00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:54.221
and it is a big challenge as well.
I don't know how I'm going to do this.

00:03:54.462 --> 00:03:57.971
On the other hand, there will be sporting
greats, so it's a great pleasure

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:01.651
and opportunity for me to talk
to them and ask them some things,

00:04:01.885 --> 00:04:04.325
to engage them so that they speak.

00:04:09.220 --> 00:04:11.420
Željko Obradović is special.

00:04:13.420 --> 00:04:18.660
He's from my industry.
He's a player who became a coach.

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:23.740
What he has achieved, no one
else has when it comes to

00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:26.660
ball sports at a top level.

00:04:26.940 --> 00:04:31.964
And I don't believe that anyone
else will be able to repeat it.

00:04:32.890 --> 00:04:38.117
He quickly reached the top.

00:04:38.940 --> 00:04:42.380
And remained on it
for an incredibly long time.

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:46.540
That is what makes him special.
There's another personal matter.

00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:51.820
In 2014, we worked together
in the same city.

00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:59.460
He was the coach of the Fenerbahçe,
and I was coaching Beşiktaş.

00:04:59.860 --> 00:05:05.180
As we had mutual friends,
they tired to introduce us-

00:05:05.740 --> 00:05:10.900
to go out for a coffee or dinner
together. Of course, I wanted that.

00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:17.780
However, you know how it often
happens when you live in the same city:

00:05:17.980 --> 00:05:20.140
"I'll leave it for tomorrow
because I have a match,

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:23.980
then for the following week,"
and so a year passes.

00:05:24.260 --> 00:05:27.660
After that, I moved to London,
and that’s it.

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:33.365
That is one of those little big
things where I often wondered,

00:05:33.765 --> 00:05:38.600
"Why did it have to be that way?
Why did I let that happen?"

00:05:39.403 --> 00:05:40.998
I had a year.

00:05:41.732 --> 00:05:45.248
But dear God sees everything-
now I have the opportunity

00:05:45.411 --> 00:05:48.771
and I don’t want to miss it.

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:07.417
Željko, on behalf of all of us,
it is a great honor to host you.

00:06:08.342 --> 00:06:12.753
I know you have many obligations,
you're always short on time,

00:06:13.004 --> 00:06:17.003
you have preseason matches and
the problems that come with them.

00:06:17.178 --> 00:06:21.019
Therefore, on behalf of the
entire team, I thank you.

00:06:22.900 --> 00:06:28.220
First, I want to ask you how satisfied
you are with Partizan's perfomance-

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:31.220
thank God, you're doing well.

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:34.260
Currently, Partizan is awaiting
the outcome and this is

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:36.500
an important part
of the season for you.

00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:43.420
Thank you and I'm glad to have
the opportunity to talk to you.

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:47.900
Because you come from my
industry and we're both coaches.

00:06:48.220 --> 00:06:55.260
You are someone who understands me.
This moment is important to us.

00:06:55.580 --> 00:07:00.740
I tried to explain to the players that
every next game is like a final.

00:07:01.020 --> 00:07:04.500
The only way to continue
competing in the Euroleague

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:06.780
and the ABA League
is precisely that-

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.220
to approach every
game like a final.

00:07:09.460 --> 00:07:13.100
In a way, there's a lot of pressure,
and on the other hand,

00:07:13.340 --> 00:07:16.780
I'm pleased because
I'm doing what I do best.

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.180
You're right. You know what ...

00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:26.904
While preparing for this interview
I noticed that it would be both easy

00:07:27.052 --> 00:07:29.068
and difficult for me at the same time.

00:07:29.407 --> 00:07:33.247
Easy because you often appear
with journalists, you're open

00:07:33.362 --> 00:07:35.183
and ready for conversation.

00:07:35.418 --> 00:07:42.114
You often appear in the studios,
podcasts, seminars, various series.

00:07:42.293 --> 00:07:45.374
There's a lot of material about
you with excellent topics,

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:47.999
questions, and exhaustive answers-
and it's all excellent.

00:07:48.233 --> 00:07:51.593
On the other hand, everything
has already been said and it's

00:07:51.842 --> 00:07:56.012
very difficult to find something
that we don't already know about you-

00:07:56.206 --> 00:07:58.246
and I would like to ask you just that.

00:07:58.433 --> 00:08:01.723
Because it's an exception
that's very interesting to me.

00:08:02.004 --> 00:08:07.856
Often the best coaches are geniuses
of tactics or discipline fanatics.

00:08:08.340 --> 00:08:11.645
Often they're closed,
they don't give much away

00:08:11.870 --> 00:08:17.525
or they're so introverted or in that way
they maintain some charisma

00:08:17.735 --> 00:08:21.900
through their mystique,
through a sense of untouchability.

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:26.260
On the other hand, you're open-
you allow people

00:08:26.460 --> 00:08:28.860
to watch training sessions.

00:08:29.037 --> 00:08:32.010
You are a guest at seminars
and on podcasts.

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:34.135
How do you explain that?

00:08:34.680 --> 00:08:38.220
The simplest answer is that
I don't know how to be someone else.

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:45.620
I’m who I am.
I behave like a coach.

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:51.340
I want to go back to the fact
that this is 2025, and that the flow

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:55.260
of information is such that it's
simply impossible to hide something.

00:08:55.540 --> 00:08:58.660
And that's why I'm open
and ready to share with all those

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:04.300
who think that I can
help by sharing knowledge.

00:09:04.980 --> 00:09:09.140
I don't know how much of it is possible
or how much it's interesting to people.

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:13.260
But everything I know,
I want to share, and many people

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:15.660
come to my training sessions.

00:09:15.900 --> 00:09:20.660
And I think it's up to them to decide
how they'll apply the things they like.

00:09:20.860 --> 00:09:23.980
Just as I once watched others,
worked with the late professor,

00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:25.940
or with Dušan Ivković.

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:30.860
I took their experiences and applied
them when working with players.

00:09:31.100 --> 00:09:34.780
Which is good, as you yourself know,
because you're also a successful coach.

00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:39.100
This conversation that I'm having
with you is unique because

00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:42.340
for the first time, I'm talking
to someone who I’m sure

00:09:42.455 --> 00:09:44.415
understands exactly who I am.

00:09:44.609 --> 00:09:48.384
And that is-I'm a coach, just like you.
-Bravo. Do you consider...

00:09:48.509 --> 00:09:50.884
You're a little older
than me, but not much.

00:09:51.059 --> 00:09:53.767
I don't think there's a big age
difference between us.

00:09:53.906 --> 00:09:57.226
And today, more things happen
in one year than before in eight.

00:09:57.500 --> 00:10:03.300
I don't want to talk about politics,
but the system of civic sports education

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:07.580
in the former Yugoslavia
was exceptional.

00:10:07.860 --> 00:10:11.700
Somehow, we were all,
as we in Dalmatia often say,

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:15.020
more or less the same.

00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:18.100
We all had the same sneakers.
We had the same dinner.

00:10:18.420 --> 00:10:27.060
Did growing up like that help you
as a player and later as a coach?

00:10:29.060 --> 00:10:33.940
When camaraderie reigned?
-Certainly, it did.

00:10:34.500 --> 00:10:39.460
If we go back to those times
when we lived together...

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:44.780
Anyone who tried to stand out
in some way,

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:50.980
perhaps by having better sneakers
or a T-shirt, would be ridiculed.

00:10:52.180 --> 00:10:56.700
At that moment, it was normal
for us all to be the same.

00:10:56.980 --> 00:11:00.580
We were a team,
we encouraged each other.

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:03.900
Individuality is important,

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:08.580
but when you grow up
in such an environment...

00:11:09.220 --> 00:11:14.020
What mattered most during that time
was that we had parents, school,

00:11:14.260 --> 00:11:18.460
and real teachers and professors
who taught us about life-

00:11:18.740 --> 00:11:25.020
not just about studying
and finishing school.

00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:30.344
But we also had a different kind
of education-life on the street.

00:11:30.507 --> 00:11:34.507
I don't mean the kind of street life
that would lead us to ruin.

00:11:34.646 --> 00:11:37.796
The street helped shape us
into better people.

00:11:37.947 --> 00:11:40.805
It taught us to respect others
and to recognize those

00:11:41.009 --> 00:11:43.609
who weren’t genuine.

00:11:43.809 --> 00:11:46.890
That is how we became
good people,

00:11:47.023 --> 00:11:49.586
and we learned to appreciate
true values.

00:11:49.848 --> 00:11:55.977
I believe that today’s generations
also have the opportunity

00:11:56.836 --> 00:11:59.744
to connect with those same values.

00:12:02.780 --> 00:12:08.180
Today, in the 21st century,
as humanity continues to evolve,

00:12:08.262 --> 00:12:10.782
some values have
always remained important.

00:12:10.873 --> 00:12:12.833
I hope that will remain true.

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:19.980
At that time, the conditions weren't
the easiest, but they were ideal.

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:23.367
You say that the best gift
you ever received was a bicycle,

00:12:23.501 --> 00:12:26.132
and that's because
the training center was far away.

00:12:26.332 --> 00:12:29.023
You needed the help
getting to the practice.

00:12:29.135 --> 00:12:31.765
And then you also say
there was only one field

00:12:31.891 --> 00:12:34.011
to play basketball in
with only one or two balls.

00:12:34.158 --> 00:12:36.598
If you lose the game, you must wait
two hours for the next one.

00:12:36.736 --> 00:12:40.109
All of those conditions made you
stronger. Nothing was easy.

00:12:40.556 --> 00:12:43.701
Giving up was the easiest thing,
but all those conditions

00:12:43.886 --> 00:12:46.187
pushed you to overcome
all the hurdles.

00:12:46.660 --> 00:12:51.820
That's how champions are made,
that's how special people are made.

00:12:52.440 --> 00:12:55.160
Nothing is better
than the feeling of pride

00:12:55.274 --> 00:12:58.443
after you overcome all of that
because you know it wasn't easy.

00:12:58.890 --> 00:13:01.660
You had to fight. Life is a battle.

00:13:01.940 --> 00:13:05.180
You always have to fight
for anything in life,

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:07.860
and that concept is
very emphasized in sports.

00:13:08.100 --> 00:13:12.260
Exactly that... I remember
that first gift, the second one,

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:17.260
and the first balls I got. Sometimes,
the most important thing for us

00:13:17.344 --> 00:13:19.424
was to have two balls
during a game of basketball.

00:13:19.605 --> 00:13:21.655
God forbid something happens
to one ball we played with,

00:13:21.820 --> 00:13:23.936
and we didn't have
the second one around...

00:13:24.079 --> 00:13:26.532
But that did happen a few times, and
we just played with some other props.

00:13:28.087 --> 00:13:31.392
I remember back in our apartment,
well actually, in our house,

00:13:31.531 --> 00:13:34.517
we had a curtain rod
and a ping-pong ball attached to it.

00:13:34.704 --> 00:13:37.904
I would spend all-day
trying to do hoops with that.

00:13:38.011 --> 00:13:41.736
I did that with my best man,
who grew up in Čačak.

00:13:41.904 --> 00:13:44.939
I am immensely proud of
those kinds of friendships.

00:13:45.073 --> 00:13:48.298
We would do that all day and
act like that was a basketball game.

00:13:48.427 --> 00:13:50.962
I was so happy
when I asked my late father

00:13:51.073 --> 00:13:54.048
to make a basketball hoop on a pole
in the street next to my house,

00:13:54.175 --> 00:13:57.815
so that we could play there.
There was no end to that happiness.

00:13:57.954 --> 00:14:01.283
Having the hoop there meant that
whenever I had some free time,

00:14:01.388 --> 00:14:07.712
I could just go out and play in the
street. That kind of happiness...

00:14:08.980 --> 00:14:11.620
I don't know how to explain that.

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:15.970
There is nothing to compare
that kind of satisfaction to.

00:14:16.860 --> 00:14:21.820
Do you remember the transfer from the
junior team in Borac to your first team?

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:24.020
Maybe not your first,
but one of the first games,

00:14:24.260 --> 00:14:26.060
the first time
going into the locker room...

00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:28.500
It wasn't easy to get in back then
because Borac was a good club.

00:14:28.725 --> 00:14:30.765
You had to stay with them
until you turned 28 years old.

00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:34.740
From what I remember and from what
I read, you asked professor Nikolić

00:14:34.854 --> 00:14:37.355
if you could go on a loan. He didn't
allow it and told you to stay

00:14:37.457 --> 00:14:41.230
and play here. Do you remember
those beginnings in the first team?

00:14:41.402 --> 00:14:44.246
Was it difficult?
Was that a dream come true?

00:14:44.446 --> 00:14:46.574
Were you proud?
How did you feel back then?

00:14:46.776 --> 00:14:52.113
I grew up in an environment with Kićo,
Radmilo, Vlade, Arsić, and Drobnjak,

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:57.060
not to mention everybody,
all the good players now...

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:01.780
I came into the team as a junior and
was the country's champion at the time.

00:15:02.060 --> 00:15:06.900
The only title Borac had from Čačak
was from my generation,

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:10.780
where I was the captain, the best
player, the best shooting guard.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:15.780
Then, in the year 1978.,
an incredible thing happened.

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:19.940
Professor Nikolić, a champion of
Yugoslavia from the club Manila,

00:15:20.140 --> 00:15:26.580
came to Borac as an advisor.
He was the man who came every week,

00:15:26.820 --> 00:15:31.540
held training sessions, and so on...
I started working with him and realized

00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:36.220
that what I thought was basketball,
as a playmaker and shooting guard,

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:40.260
had nothing to do with
basketball as he perceived it.

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:44.660
I fell under his strong influence
and started changing as a player.

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:49.740
I started playing as a playmaker,
and I still carry what he taught me.

00:15:49.980 --> 00:15:55.540
But exactly that... You prepared
for this talk very well!

00:15:55.772 --> 00:15:59.632
That was the year I wanted to play,
and I think for a young player,

00:15:59.733 --> 00:16:02.710
the most important thing is to have
the opportunity to play somewhere.

00:16:02.878 --> 00:16:06.859
True. -I didn't want to sit on the bench
because there were so many good players

00:16:07.172 --> 00:16:11.101
in front of me on the court. I told the
professor, or maybe it was him who said

00:16:11.326 --> 00:16:13.646
that he heard I wanted to go to Radnički
Kragujevac. I told him that was true,

00:16:13.793 --> 00:16:17.076
because I wanted to play, and he told me
I would get a chance to play here, too.

00:16:17.271 --> 00:16:20.750
I asked him if that was something
he could guarantee or promise,

00:16:20.980 --> 00:16:25.260
and he said it was. Of course,
I trusted someone like my professor

00:16:25.580 --> 00:16:31.540
and my late coach, Slobodan Conja
Koprivica. So, I stayed in that club.

00:16:31.820 --> 00:16:37.580
One of the decisive moments
in my career as a player

00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:41.980
was when Borac dropped out of
the first league the following year.

00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:44.380
A new generation
of players stepped in

00:16:44.550 --> 00:16:47.310
as the older ones went to serve
in the military or went to other clubs.

00:16:47.465 --> 00:16:49.905
The young players
were given a chance to play,

00:16:50.029 --> 00:16:52.588
and I was given the opportunity to play.
That's when doors started opening.

00:16:52.722 --> 00:16:55.482
Things have to happen...
-That was pure luck.

00:16:55.574 --> 00:17:00.268
Sadly, my club dropped out of
the old Yugoslavian league,

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:03.360
where we were previously taking fifth
place. We even played the Korać Cup.

00:17:03.487 --> 00:17:05.924
But that season, due to
traveling and everything else,

00:17:06.035 --> 00:17:08.155
led to us dropping out of the league,
older players leaving,

00:17:08.239 --> 00:17:10.798
and younger players
getting to step in.

00:17:11.006 --> 00:17:14.299
From that moment on, my career
as a player started taking off.

00:17:14.740 --> 00:17:18.180
Everybody has that one moment.
It's luck and openness to new things,

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:22.900
but only big people and big players
seize that opportunity.

00:17:23.460 --> 00:17:26.420
That's exactly it.
That's that difference.

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:29.300
Okay, so you were playing for Partizan,
you were on the national team,

00:17:29.500 --> 00:17:34.500
everything was going like clockwork,
as we say in Dalmatia.

00:17:35.180 --> 00:17:40.740
When you turned 30, you did something
that, from today's perspective,

00:17:41.860 --> 00:17:45.620
is the best thing you could have done
for your career.

00:17:45.843 --> 00:17:49.243
But you know, my whole life,
well 40 years of it,

00:17:49.530 --> 00:17:54.945
I've dedicated to football and sport...
Kroos left Real Madrid at 34 last year,

00:17:55.554 --> 00:17:58.960
but a player, especially a good one like
you at the time, wants to keep playing.

00:17:59.105 --> 00:18:02.210
You were still waiting to play in the
European championship and win medals.

00:18:02.354 --> 00:18:05.741
How did you make the decision to leave?
Who did you consult with? How?

00:18:06.860 --> 00:18:11.180
I talked with myself. At the time
I was the captain of the national team,

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:13.580
and we knew we would
win gold most likely,

00:18:13.860 --> 00:18:18.060
and that I was supposed to be the one to
raise the cup... Something in me was...

00:18:18.260 --> 00:18:21.100
Kićo called me during the night

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:23.940
while we were returning from Poreč
and national team training.

00:18:24.140 --> 00:18:27.820
My late best man Sava and I
went to see him and he told us that

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:31.500
I had to take on the team now
or they would get another trainer.

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:36.460
At that moment, I made the decision.
How do I explain that to you, Slaven?

00:18:37.300 --> 00:18:41.060
At that moment, nobody
believed it but Kićo and Sava.

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:45.460
Not even my best friends believed me.
Everybody told me I was insane.

00:18:45.700 --> 00:18:50.700
That was the first time in my career
that I was close to some very serious

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:54.460
contracts with one club from
Yugoslavia and Germany.

00:18:54.700 --> 00:18:57.755
We were talking about a lot of money
there. For the first time in my life...

00:18:57.847 --> 00:18:59.327
You never played abroad. -Yes.

00:18:59.535 --> 00:19:03.801
You were a fantastic player. You were
a playmaker, you were important...

00:19:04.061 --> 00:19:09.381
But I knew that what was being offered
was something I wanted to do.

00:19:09.647 --> 00:19:11.989
But that position would wait for you.
-Yes, it would.

00:19:12.195 --> 00:19:14.755
Rađa wasn't the only one to say...
-But Kićo didn't want to wait for me.

00:19:14.851 --> 00:19:17.458
Everybody was saying that you're
the one for the job. You said yourself

00:19:17.586 --> 00:19:20.395
five minutes ago that you were the one
writing down the training schedules.

00:19:20.518 --> 00:19:24.106
Yes. -You knew it was coming your way.
Maybe not in Partizan, though.

00:19:24.213 --> 00:19:28.692
As the saying says, opportunities are
there for those who seize them-true.

00:19:28.896 --> 00:19:31.785
But you knew that was certain,
that it was coming your way.

00:19:31.907 --> 00:19:33.870
I always said that
once you make a decision,

00:19:33.956 --> 00:19:35.956
you accept it and live with it.

00:19:36.056 --> 00:19:39.175
You don't go back in time and think
if other options would have been better.

00:19:39.351 --> 00:19:45.706
You make a decision, and you live with
it. I made my decision then with Sava.

00:19:47.568 --> 00:19:50.344
They didn't want to wait for the
European championship to end,

00:19:50.436 --> 00:19:58.243
so I put my foot down. Of course, at
that moment, it all seemed unbelievable.

00:19:58.598 --> 00:20:02.758
Afterwards they... We started making
a team and working with it.

00:20:02.932 --> 00:20:07.602
Whenever we played matches,
we would be losing by 50 points.

00:20:08.100 --> 00:20:12.540
Naturally, people began laughing at
Partizan's choice to sign these players.

00:20:12.780 --> 00:20:17.140
A lot of these young players
from numerous national, junior,

00:20:17.380 --> 00:20:22.660
and senior teams, like Saša Danilović,
Đorđević, Rebrača, Šilobad, Lončar,

00:20:23.460 --> 00:20:26.020
Nakić also joined from another team,

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:29.580
Vlado Dragutinović
and Koprivica from IMT,

00:20:30.260 --> 00:20:34.940
Stevanović from Radnički,
and made them into a team.

00:20:35.340 --> 00:20:38.780
The only experienced player we had
was the late Dragiša Šarić.

00:20:38.980 --> 00:20:42.940
We first started with the preparations
and then with the tournaments.

00:20:43.220 --> 00:20:45.820
Of course, after that,
everything started looking better.

00:20:46.060 --> 00:20:49.500
We started winning, and people were
curious to see what was going on there.

00:20:49.740 --> 00:20:54.780
I became a person that doesn't
sleep for two months.

00:20:55.180 --> 00:20:59.620
Every exercise I gave out
was thought through

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:04.080
so I could have all the answers for
the players. I always had the answers.

00:21:04.283 --> 00:21:08.420
I was lucky that they put their trust
in me because I was their captain.

00:21:09.580 --> 00:21:12.481
As for my humanity
and character traits,

00:21:12.598 --> 00:21:15.090
they had no issue with that,
but their concern was,

00:21:15.196 --> 00:21:17.443
"Let's see if this coach
actually knows what he's doing."

00:21:17.577 --> 00:21:19.417
And I was showing them that I do.

00:21:19.539 --> 00:21:22.098
I was fortunate to have
the late professor by my side.

00:21:22.232 --> 00:21:25.072
He was teaching me things,
and I was just absorbing them all.

00:21:25.226 --> 00:21:27.786
I spent two years in Partizan.
After the first fantastic year,

00:21:27.916 --> 00:21:31.756
I didn't go chasing after the money
and work abroad.

00:21:31.885 --> 00:21:35.231
I stayed alongside the professor for
free in Partizan for a whole year.

00:21:35.446 --> 00:21:38.958
There wasn't any money,
and the situation was challenging.

00:21:39.115 --> 00:21:42.915
Still, I loved doing that,
so I stayed there to better myself.

00:21:43.215 --> 00:21:47.575
When I look back at those times, I
congratulate myself for doing just that.

00:21:48.220 --> 00:21:56.420
Phenomenal. You said that you
received the best compliment

00:21:56.940 --> 00:22:00.660
from Duda Jurković,
who you are connected to.

00:22:01.300 --> 00:22:06.780
He said he had never seen a coach or
a man with such great intuition as you.

00:22:07.340 --> 00:22:12.420
Yes. -Do you rely on your intuition
when making substitutes

00:22:12.740 --> 00:22:19.540
and for more significant decisions like
a career break or choosing a new club?

00:22:20.780 --> 00:22:25.340
Intuition is more connected to
these situations regarding matches

00:22:26.020 --> 00:22:31.100
and times when you have to react fast,
usually during the game

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:36.385
or during summer when you are choosing
between several good players.

00:22:36.590 --> 00:22:39.932
Everybody knows who a good player is,
but you always want to find out

00:22:40.018 --> 00:22:42.498
more information like
what kind of a person they are,

00:22:42.633 --> 00:22:44.768
if he will change the team atmosphere,
if he will fit in...

00:22:45.020 --> 00:22:49.740
But intuition is needed during training
and games when deciding on substitutes,

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:54.540
defense, attacks... As I already said,
you make decisions and live with them.

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:59.820
I don't know a single person
that always makes the right decisions.

00:23:00.100 --> 00:23:06.500
I think a person like that
doesn't exist. -You. -No, no way.

00:23:07.220 --> 00:23:09.180
A person like that doesn't exist.
-You are close...

00:23:09.420 --> 00:23:12.660
You make decisions
and live with them.

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:16.344
Going back in time and thinking
what you could have done differently

00:23:16.569 --> 00:23:19.453
is a waste of time.
You make decisions, live with them,

00:23:19.605 --> 00:23:21.845
and tell yourself it is
the best possible decision.

00:23:21.975 --> 00:23:24.141
Decisions have to be made, though.
-They have to be made.

00:23:24.211 --> 00:23:26.291
Yes, they have to be made.
-That's the essence.

00:23:26.459 --> 00:23:29.539
I am lucky to have some people
around me who I respect and love

00:23:29.692 --> 00:23:31.852
and whose opinions
I care about a lot.

00:23:31.965 --> 00:23:35.102
But I was always the one who made
the decision in the end. -Yes.

00:23:35.555 --> 00:23:40.149
That is my decision. It concerns
my life, my team, my family...

00:23:40.297 --> 00:23:42.657
I want to be the one
making the decisions.

00:23:42.794 --> 00:23:45.938
But of course, I will listen
to the people I trust

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:54.211
and who are always there for me.
Sometimes, you win, and it feels good.

00:23:54.820 --> 00:24:00.399
If I open my phone after a win,
I know I will see 200 messages.

00:24:00.635 --> 00:24:03.172
But when we lose, I know
there will be those five...

00:24:03.289 --> 00:24:06.508
Those five people... -That’s
the first ring that protects you.

00:24:06.860 --> 00:24:09.700
Those are your people,
and they are always the best.

00:24:10.020 --> 00:24:14.700
Okay. Let’s talk about that a bit.
When you're unemployed,

00:24:14.980 --> 00:24:17.820
you choose a club.
Now you're picking players.

00:24:18.140 --> 00:24:22.780
Of course, there are scouts.
-Yes. -I read that, it's detailed,

00:24:23.060 --> 00:24:26.780
you get reports. In the end, you know
what kind of player someone is.

00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:29.580
The basketball world is also small.

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:35.180
Even from coaches, teammates,
and barbers, informations are gathered.

00:24:35.460 --> 00:24:39.940
When selecting, if you
have to separate something,

00:24:40.300 --> 00:24:44.820
do you go by character or quality?
Would you take...

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:50.060
Someone who scores 15-20 points,
but isn't the best in the locker room.

00:24:50.540 --> 00:24:54.740
Or the opposite?
If you can't find the ideal one,

00:24:54.980 --> 00:24:58.620
because the ideal won't come to Partizan,
but wants to stay at Real. -That’s right.

00:24:58.900 --> 00:25:02.460
How do you react?
Where do you draw the line?

00:25:03.820 --> 00:25:07.340
It's not easy,
but it's a very good question.

00:25:09.060 --> 00:25:11.980
Recognizing a good player,
everyone can do that easily.

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:14.700
When he's good, it's easy.
But these other things matter.

00:25:14.980 --> 00:25:20.500
I've always said that the most important
thing is that he's a good player.

00:25:21.620 --> 00:25:25.660
When we have three point guards,
and we also have this fourth one...

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:30.900
Let him come too. When someone is good,
they will give you something good.

00:25:31.140 --> 00:25:33.580
But when someone is bad,
they can't give you anything.

00:25:33.820 --> 00:25:36.220
That's the first thing.
You recognize a good player.

00:25:36.460 --> 00:25:39.620
When building a team,
you create a composition.

00:25:39.860 --> 00:25:41.940
There's a way to build
a basketball team,

00:25:42.180 --> 00:25:44.340
by positions, and you look
at what you need.

00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:47.300
And during the season,
when injuries happen,

00:25:47.500 --> 00:25:54.300
when you have a problem... Your
number 5, your big man, gets injured.

00:25:54.580 --> 00:25:57.340
But there are no good
number fives on the market.

00:25:57.620 --> 00:25:59.820
We don’t have to take
a number five,

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:06.020
let’s get a player that everyone
on the team will say is good.

00:26:06.340 --> 00:26:09.540
Not just take some average player
and say, "He won’t help us."

00:26:09.780 --> 00:26:13.340
Quality comes first, always.
-Absolutely. -But as a coach,

00:26:13.580 --> 00:26:19.613
you also have to convince someone.
"You're prone to these things.

00:26:19.895 --> 00:26:25.145
Can you change a little?"
You have to understand team chemistry.

00:26:25.502 --> 00:26:30.949
The team is always the most important.
I will always defend the team.

00:26:31.180 --> 00:26:35.488
Coaches defend the team.
-And themselves. -That’s just how it is.

00:26:36.106 --> 00:26:40.395
There’s no ideal.
I always use that phrase.

00:26:40.740 --> 00:26:45.700
We can't buy 12 Michael Jordans.
-Yes. -Or 12 Toni Kukočs.

00:26:46.220 --> 00:26:50.500
12 Paspaljs, Divacs, I don’t know.
That’s not possible.

00:26:50.780 --> 00:26:53.340
Someone has to play a secondary role.
When they asked me...

00:26:53.580 --> 00:27:00.060
I’m grateful that I had the chance
to coach the best players.

00:27:01.060 --> 00:27:03.940
When they ask me about the best,
everyone knows who they are.

00:27:04.220 --> 00:27:07.820
But I remember those who helped
me and my team become champions,

00:27:08.220 --> 00:27:12.620
and many don’t know about them.
The ones in secondary roles.

00:27:12.860 --> 00:27:17.209
They will do everything for the team
so that we can be at the top.

00:27:17.418 --> 00:27:20.561
I always remember those players.
The ones who are the best...

00:27:20.780 --> 00:27:23.820
Recently, there was a list of the
25 best Euroleague players,

00:27:24.020 --> 00:27:27.060
I've coached 15 of them.
Everyone knows who they are.

00:27:27.151 --> 00:27:29.991
Not just me, others coached
them too, of course.

00:27:30.580 --> 00:27:36.420
But without those who do,
it's an ugly word, the dirty work,

00:27:36.740 --> 00:27:41.420
who do the other things... -The miners.
-The miners, exactly. Thank you.

00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:44.768
Without them,
there’s no success.

00:27:45.657 --> 00:27:49.002
We talked over lunch
about the Premier League.

00:27:49.417 --> 00:27:52.619
You often have a dilemma.
I can't buy a winger

00:27:52.980 --> 00:27:56.300
who scores goals, assists,
and helps the full-back.

00:27:56.500 --> 00:28:01.700
That player goes to City, Arsenal.
At West Ham, you have that dilemma.

00:28:01.980 --> 00:28:06.620
There’s another dilemma. I have
to take a player who proved himself

00:28:06.860 --> 00:28:13.700
at a lower level, in Switzerland,
Belgium, Croatia, Serbia, etc.

00:28:14.300 --> 00:28:18.900
I hope he will be able to...
-It implies better motivation.

00:28:19.340 --> 00:28:23.100
And quality. Or someone who
succeeded in the Premier League,

00:28:23.380 --> 00:28:26.740
but in the last two years declined,
either due to injury or poor form,

00:28:26.940 --> 00:28:34.260
and now I hope that my staff and I
can bring him back to that level.

00:28:35.940 --> 00:28:41.380
It's not ideal. -Slaven, I told you
over the lunch, you worked in a league

00:28:41.660 --> 00:28:47.380
that’s like the NBA. The English
league in football is incredible.

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:51.820
There’s no one who loves football
who doesn’t watch the English league.

00:28:52.060 --> 00:28:57.380
Full respect to the Spanish, Germans,
Italians, but the English are the English.

00:28:58.020 --> 00:29:05.580
It’s unreal. The organization, the players.
When you look at how it all works...

00:29:05.860 --> 00:29:11.100
I told you, my dream is to watch
the FA Cup final live. -We'll go.

00:29:11.820 --> 00:29:17.420
Or the NCAA final in America.
I know what you mean.

00:29:17.660 --> 00:29:21.340
We talked about how you
reached that level...

00:29:22.780 --> 00:29:25.460
Working in the English league
is incredible.

00:29:26.260 --> 00:29:29.340
It’s the NBA of Europe.

00:29:29.940 --> 00:29:33.180
Now you have your team,
your staff.

00:29:33.780 --> 00:29:41.243
Explain a bit, for young coaches,
how do you choose your staff.

00:29:41.820 --> 00:29:46.660
Just like with players, quality
and character. It’s the same with staff.

00:29:47.580 --> 00:29:52.540
Their ability, and on
the other side, loyalty. -Yes.

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:59.220
Of course, both are important.
-In my coaching staff,

00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:04.700
I have three people who were
with me for seven years at Fenerbahçe.

00:30:04.900 --> 00:30:07.140
Vlade Andrović, Bata Zimonjić,
the conditioning coach,

00:30:07.340 --> 00:30:13.980
and Scierdo, I worked with him
at Joventut in 1993. Now it’s 2025.

00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:20.740
We stayed in touch. I called him.
Now I’ll give an example, Bogdan Karaičić.

00:30:21.780 --> 00:30:24.580
He worked with the national team
under Igor Kokoškov.

00:30:24.780 --> 00:30:28.740
Igor recommended him. I told him
to call him in for an interview.

00:30:28.980 --> 00:30:31.740
We talked for five minutes.
Five minutes.

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:34.940
I asked a few questions
and said, "OK."

00:30:35.180 --> 00:30:37.940
You’ll be on my coaching staff.
About a month passed,

00:30:38.140 --> 00:30:43.180
while they were with the national team.
Igor calls me and asks what’s going on,

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:48.980
the kid is asking. I told him it’s fine.
There’s nothing more to discuss.

00:30:49.260 --> 00:30:52.740
Five minutes with someone
is enough for me to see

00:30:53.060 --> 00:30:56.380
how much they know and can do.
That’s knowledge.

00:30:56.860 --> 00:30:59.980
The other thing is loyalty.

00:31:00.460 --> 00:31:04.220
I build relationships where
I am equal with them.

00:31:04.420 --> 00:31:07.540
They have the right to say
whatever they want,

00:31:07.740 --> 00:31:12.020
during a game or in training.
I take in all that information,

00:31:12.180 --> 00:31:14.980
but in the end, I make
the decision. That’s it.

00:31:15.180 --> 00:31:17.620
Wherever I worked,
I was lucky...

00:31:17.820 --> 00:31:26.220
From Partizan, Joventut, Real,
Benetton, Panathinaikos,

00:31:26.700 --> 00:31:29.780
Fenerbahçe, and here,
I worked with amazing people.

00:31:30.020 --> 00:31:34.740
Now I joke with Neven Spahija,
who is coaching in Venice.

00:31:34.980 --> 00:31:37.700
Two assistants who were with me
in Treviso are now his assistants.

00:31:37.900 --> 00:31:42.340
I worked with them in 1997.
So I send him messages:

00:31:42.580 --> 00:31:47.420
"It’s easy for you when you work
with them." We’re good friends.

00:31:47.780 --> 00:31:51.220
They are all wonderful people,
amazing coaches.

00:31:51.460 --> 00:31:54.460
I always wondered
if I was that lucky.

00:31:55.220 --> 00:31:58.780
I chose my assistants.
There used to be just one assistant.

00:31:58.980 --> 00:32:01.300
Now it’s an entire coaching staff.

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:05.540
When I left Joventut,
the one who is now my assistant,

00:32:05.740 --> 00:32:08.820
the coach sitting next to me...
I found him there.

00:32:08.980 --> 00:32:12.220
A great person, we became friends.
He’s like a brother to me.

00:32:12.420 --> 00:32:15.260
And Vlade, no need to even mention him.
We grew up together, played in Čačak.

00:32:15.389 --> 00:32:19.869
Bata as well. The two in Treviso,
wonderful people. I found them there too.

00:32:20.046 --> 00:32:23.618
I didn’t choose them.
I was told they were there.

00:32:23.788 --> 00:32:27.188
Is that luck? Maybe it is,
or maybe it’s my way of working.

00:32:27.341 --> 00:32:32.135
To give them confidence.
I’m not someone you just nod to.

00:32:32.642 --> 00:32:37.924
The moment you do that, it’s over.
Tell me if you disagree.

00:32:38.197 --> 00:32:43.814
He’s an assistant coach,
and he’s a friend.

00:32:44.049 --> 00:32:49.180
Are you a control freak,
do you need to know everything,

00:32:49.540 --> 00:32:55.563
or do you say who does what?
The contact is daily.

00:32:56.700 --> 00:33:02.820
Do you need to know everything? -No.
I’m a philanthropist. I love people.

00:33:03.340 --> 00:33:07.180
I trust people. If that’s the case,
I trust them too.

00:33:07.460 --> 00:33:15.100
Trust sometimes leads to disappointment.
Not only in coaching, but in life.

00:33:15.740 --> 00:33:20.900
I can’t change myself
after hitting the wall three times.

00:33:21.100 --> 00:33:24.540
I can’t. I keep loving
people and I’ll keep loving.

00:33:24.780 --> 00:33:29.340
That experience sometimes helps
to slow down.

00:33:29.580 --> 00:33:34.020
Or it gives you the situation
to find a reason to talk.

00:33:34.260 --> 00:33:36.820
I trusted you,
and this is how you repay me.

00:33:37.060 --> 00:33:40.740
Let’s see if you’re wrong
or if I’m wrong.

00:33:40.980 --> 00:33:44.580
Conversation is the most important
for people to understand each other.

00:33:44.780 --> 00:33:47.500
I’m going back to what
we were talking about.

00:33:47.700 --> 00:33:50.980
Saying "sorry" when you make
a mistake is so easy,

00:33:51.260 --> 00:33:54.060
but people don’t use it that often.
-Well done.

00:33:54.300 --> 00:34:01.460
I had lunch yesterday
with Nemanja Vidić, a legend.

00:34:01.780 --> 00:34:06.260
He says it’s all about professionalism.
He brings in professionals.

00:34:06.540 --> 00:34:12.540
They don’t have to be friends.
I say OK, but there has to be a balance.

00:34:13.100 --> 00:34:19.180
When things aren’t going well,
you need someone who will hug you

00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:22.900
and comfort you,
or you do that for them.

00:34:25.060 --> 00:34:29.060
There needs to be some balance.
-When the Euroleague game ends,

00:34:29.300 --> 00:34:32.580
I’m the last one to leave
the office. Always.

00:34:32.980 --> 00:34:36.100
There are a thousand reasons
why I talk to everyone,

00:34:36.340 --> 00:34:38.460
and I also have a press conference.

00:34:38.700 --> 00:34:41.140
It has never happened that we
lost an important game,

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:45.180
and didn’t stay together.
Coaches. We stay and talk.

00:34:45.420 --> 00:34:47.900
Those are the moments when
they know they need to be with me,

00:34:48.100 --> 00:34:50.900
that I’m struggling.
I know it’s hard for them too.

00:34:51.060 --> 00:34:53.860
Then we help each other.
Without that, it’s impossible.

00:34:54.060 --> 00:34:56.180
I don’t believe
in harsh professionalism.

00:34:56.380 --> 00:34:59.620
I love Vidić. He had
a fantastic career.

00:34:59.820 --> 00:35:03.100
He probably has experience, some
reasons, but I don’t believe in that.

00:35:03.300 --> 00:35:07.780
We are humans first and foremost,
much more than professionals.

00:35:07.980 --> 00:35:15.194
That trust between us is
a prerequisite for team chemistry

00:35:15.326 --> 00:35:24.740
and for all of us to function. I often
get angry at the assistant coaches

00:35:25.740 --> 00:35:29.300
and the players during the game.
That’s the moment.

00:35:29.500 --> 00:35:33.820
They know it. After that,
it’s over. -Well done.

00:35:35.620 --> 00:35:40.300
If I repeat something to you 20 times,
and you make a mistake on the 21st time,

00:35:40.820 --> 00:35:44.940
I have to react.
And they do the same to me.

00:35:45.143 --> 00:35:48.349
Feel free to say that I made
a mistake. Of course, I did.

00:35:48.458 --> 00:35:50.662
Of course, you’re right.
What’s the problem?

00:35:50.867 --> 00:35:53.307
Who is the person who
doesn’t make mistakes?

00:35:53.422 --> 00:35:57.154
Is there such a person? I don’t know him.
Exactly. Well done. You’re...

00:36:01.300 --> 00:36:04.380
Many coaches, especially
the younger ones, in any sport,

00:36:04.620 --> 00:36:09.300
say "I play like this, and that’s it."
Bring me the players.

00:36:09.620 --> 00:36:13.058
The club can’t change 7-8 players
just to please you.

00:36:13.198 --> 00:36:15.464
On the other hand,
you succeeded in that,

00:36:15.597 --> 00:36:17.722
and the current lineup of Partizan
is an example of that.

00:36:17.821 --> 00:36:19.621
This is a new team, right? -Yes.

00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:25.060
But, Real with Sabonis,
won the championship.

00:36:26.820 --> 00:36:29.940
After he left, even though
you are European champions,

00:36:30.140 --> 00:36:32.620
you change 10 players.
-That's right.

00:36:32.820 --> 00:36:36.300
With Sabonis, you score 80,
and with the new team,

00:36:36.500 --> 00:36:43.060
you score 100 points. -Yes.
-So, your greatness is reflected in that.

00:36:43.260 --> 00:36:47.340
The model is built
around the players.

00:36:47.580 --> 00:36:52.260
We all have our own principles
and the way we like to play.

00:36:52.780 --> 00:36:54.980
In basketball, it’s this:
"We play good defense,

00:36:55.180 --> 00:36:57.540
we run on the fast break,
we score easily,

00:36:57.700 --> 00:37:00.580
we want the audience
to be satisfied, etc."

00:37:00.820 --> 00:37:04.112
Everything in that story is fine,
but only when you step onto the court

00:37:04.220 --> 00:37:06.700
you can see the quality
of the people you’ve chosen.

00:37:06.822 --> 00:37:10.271
And yes, after that in Real,
I was asked why I’m changing the team

00:37:10.497 --> 00:37:12.137
that’s European champion.

00:37:12.244 --> 00:37:14.740
I said: "Wait, people, the one
who was the most important has left."

00:37:14.790 --> 00:37:16.450
Everything revolved around him.

00:37:16.505 --> 00:37:18.425
He was the player
who loved to steal the ball,

00:37:18.500 --> 00:37:20.256
make the first pass to those
who are running,

00:37:20.318 --> 00:37:22.014
because he hated going first
into the offense.

00:37:22.096 --> 00:37:23.826
When he runs into offense…

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:26.127
I remember one game against Zaragoza,
which I always talk about.

00:37:26.230 --> 00:37:32.589
He had 45 points and 28 rebounds
in a 45-minute basketball game.

00:37:33.772 --> 00:37:35.412
What more is there to say?

00:37:35.540 --> 00:37:38.140
I had a problem with him
during training,

00:37:38.380 --> 00:37:40.900
with the double teams
we were practicing.

00:37:41.140 --> 00:37:43.380
I had never seen anything
like it in my life.

00:37:43.660 --> 00:37:46.580
Before the double team, it was like
he was playing volleyball,

00:37:46.820 --> 00:37:49.980
when the ball came to him,
he’d do this, as if he was slapping it.

00:37:50.220 --> 00:37:51.980
He could exactly, the moment
the ball was coming to him,

00:37:52.180 --> 00:37:53.500
see who was free.

00:37:53.740 --> 00:37:55.860
I asked him to do something similar
during a game.

00:37:56.100 --> 00:37:59.300
You catch the ball, then wait for them
to double-team you.

00:37:59.388 --> 00:38:01.828
He asked: "Why, coach,
when I can see everything?"

00:38:01.943 --> 00:38:03.503
What could I tell him?
-Yeah, what?

00:38:04.660 --> 00:38:08.900
That year with him was incredible.
If he hadn’t had that ankle injury,

00:38:09.140 --> 00:38:12.860
he would have dominated in the NBA too,
but he would have been a wonder

00:38:13.100 --> 00:38:15.820
with 2,20, quick thinking,
and that easy touch.

00:38:16.020 --> 00:38:19.020
Because he shot
three-pointers phenomenally.

00:38:19.500 --> 00:38:21.260
He was 2 meters and 20 tall.

00:38:21.540 --> 00:38:25.980
If he could have run a little faster,
nobody would have been better than him.

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:30.740
We changed the team,
and for his position, a man came in,

00:38:30.980 --> 00:38:34.220
who is now the sports director
of Partizan, Zoran Savić and Jan Lukas.

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:39.540
And for me, during those years in Spain,
they said I played control basketball.

00:38:39.780 --> 00:38:43.700
Then I brought in Zoran,
who was a center and could run,

00:38:43.940 --> 00:38:47.820
so, as you said, we scored
around 100 points in 8 games.

00:38:48.300 --> 00:38:51.580
Then comes the question,
"What do you say now?"

00:38:51.820 --> 00:38:54.940
I don’t know how no one understands
that everything depends on

00:38:55.180 --> 00:38:57.220
who you have in the team.
That’s it.

00:38:57.500 --> 00:38:59.700
In the end, all basketball coaches
will tell you,

00:38:59.823 --> 00:39:02.423
"The offense is fantastic,
but nobody gave their maximum

00:39:02.505 --> 00:39:04.425
if they didn’t play defense." -True.

00:39:04.940 --> 00:39:07.020
You’ll probably say
the same about football.

00:39:07.300 --> 00:39:09.820
You can have Ronaldo and Messi
and you’ll score one more goal,

00:39:10.060 --> 00:39:12.020
but if you concede easily,
you won’t win easily.

00:39:12.260 --> 00:39:14.460
Wait, if you play badly in training,
and nothing is ever really bad,

00:39:14.660 --> 00:39:21.900
and you play 5 on 5 on a smaller court,
5 defenders against 5 attackers,

00:39:22.260 --> 00:39:26.140
the defenders will always win.
-Yes. -No matter the position,

00:39:26.340 --> 00:39:29.220
you can never score as many goals
as you can concede. -Yes.

00:39:29.420 --> 00:39:31.260
These defenses are something.

00:39:31.500 --> 00:39:33.820
Okay, but regardless
of whether you're playing for fewer

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:37.726
or more points,
the denominator is the same.

00:39:37.852 --> 00:39:40.692
Every one of your teams
"sacrifices" itself. (plays selflessly)

00:39:40.861 --> 00:39:42.640
And your statement is,

00:39:42.798 --> 00:39:45.430
"All I ask from you
is to give your best."

00:39:46.700 --> 00:39:49.740
Yes, because without that,
it’s impossible. Motivation is key.

00:39:50.020 --> 00:39:52.860
There is also the fact
that it's a large number of games

00:39:53.060 --> 00:39:55.700
and not every game can be played
with the same level of motivation.

00:39:55.940 --> 00:40:03.180
That’s what I try to awaken in them,
and when it’s a 50/50 ball, let it be ours.

00:40:03.900 --> 00:40:06.460
If the ball is here, dive for it.
The crowd will reward you.

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:09.100
After that, you can miss and lose,
and they will still be with you,

00:40:09.300 --> 00:40:11.684
because they see
your desire and fight.

00:40:12.159 --> 00:40:15.039
So that’s the first prerequisite,
but it must be repeated.

00:40:15.418 --> 00:40:18.840
You can’t say it once or twice.
It must be said before every game.

00:40:19.180 --> 00:40:22.918
We are lucky to be "Partizan"
and wherever we play,

00:40:23.099 --> 00:40:24.819
there are our people.

00:40:25.660 --> 00:40:28.260
But that’s not important.
Wherever you play,

00:40:28.438 --> 00:40:31.758
the first and most basic thing
is to fight for the ball,

00:40:31.888 --> 00:40:34.648
because in that way, you show
that you have the desire to win,

00:40:34.748 --> 00:40:36.713
and if you show desire, it means
that your motivation is

00:40:36.796 --> 00:40:38.632
at the highest possible level.
A motivated person has no limits.

00:40:38.757 --> 00:40:40.424
You’re saying that, yes.

00:40:40.528 --> 00:40:43.736
Whoever lacks motivation
can’t expect,

00:40:43.933 --> 00:40:48.095
not just in sports, in basketball,
but in anything they do in life,

00:40:48.246 --> 00:40:52.467
to reach the heights
they once hoped to achieve.

00:40:52.797 --> 00:40:55.979
Everyone knows that, but only you
manage to achieve it.

00:40:56.243 --> 00:40:58.043
I don’t always succeed.

00:40:58.829 --> 00:41:05.271
Now, the season begins...
You have fifteen players? -Yes.

00:41:05.473 --> 00:41:07.473
When I was preparing
to become a coach,

00:41:07.820 --> 00:41:12.900
I went to see Wenger,
who is the coach of Arsenal.

00:41:13.220 --> 00:41:18.820
I am a young coach. -Yes.
When I arrived, he told me,

00:41:18.928 --> 00:41:21.008
"This is just like being
a manager of a bank.

00:41:21.137 --> 00:41:22.897
You’re the director of the bank."

00:41:23.580 --> 00:41:28.700
You have 25 young managers,
who have money, are good-looking,

00:41:28.900 --> 00:41:34.380
have cars, go out, but for the project,
you need 11 of them.

00:41:35.700 --> 00:41:42.100
You also know that for the next project,
you'll need 4-5 new ones, or more.

00:41:42.340 --> 00:41:44.140
Maybe all 11. -Exactly.

00:41:44.460 --> 00:41:50.660
How do you motivate
these marginal ones?

00:41:50.940 --> 00:41:53.980
Because a player feels what his role
is after the preparations. -Yes.

00:41:54.220 --> 00:41:57.020
It roughly crystallizes, doesn’t it?

00:41:57.260 --> 00:41:59.700
Maybe less in basketball,
more in football,

00:41:59.940 --> 00:42:01.660
because the score is higher?

00:42:01.940 --> 00:42:08.180
How do you maintain motivation
in those players,

00:42:08.540 --> 00:42:12.580
to play when they get the chance,
and they will get it?

00:42:13.020 --> 00:42:15.100
This is achieved through
daily conversations,

00:42:15.380 --> 00:42:18.340
after which all players must
feel that they are important.

00:42:18.580 --> 00:42:20.820
And that’s exactly
what I try to explain.

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:24.140
And of course, it's an old story that
we have 15 players on the list,

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:27.420
because practically every week
two or three are out of the game

00:42:27.620 --> 00:42:30.500
due to injuries, illness,
or something else.

00:42:30.740 --> 00:42:33.300
And of course, all of them,
when the season starts, want to play.

00:42:33.580 --> 00:42:37.460
As time goes on and as motivation
in some games naturally decreases,

00:42:37.740 --> 00:42:41.487
they start thinking about
how they could skip this one...

00:42:41.953 --> 00:42:44.737
And when one skips,
the other has to step in.

00:42:44.980 --> 00:42:48.660
And that’s it. Use your chance,
and when you use it,

00:42:49.300 --> 00:42:52.980
maybe the one who left, won’t be
in the starting five anymore,

00:42:53.220 --> 00:42:56.020
but it will be you.
That depends on you. I always say,

00:42:56.220 --> 00:42:58.620
"The playing time on the court
doesn’t depend on me,

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:01.260
it depends on them.
They decide for themselves.

00:43:01.500 --> 00:43:04.020
Not me, or the audience."

00:43:04.151 --> 00:43:06.071
I'm not naive either,
to remove from the game

00:43:06.193 --> 00:43:07.793
someone who is playing well.

00:43:08.020 --> 00:43:10.980
I understand, but we just said
that players are selfish.

00:43:11.220 --> 00:43:14.660
Of course, they are.
Once, Capello told me...

00:43:15.220 --> 00:43:18.420
He was the coach of Russia,
and I was the coach of Lokomotiv.

00:43:18.700 --> 00:43:24.300
He gave me one piece of advice,
"Never promise a player anything."

00:43:24.500 --> 00:43:28.380
But when you're buying a player,
when you invite him to the team,

00:43:28.660 --> 00:43:30.900
you have to attract him
with something, right?

00:43:31.100 --> 00:43:33.700
Yes, yes. You have to tell him
what exactly you expect from him.

00:43:33.900 --> 00:43:36.700
You have to, as we say,
give him a little candy. -Exactly.

00:43:37.380 --> 00:43:43.340
And how do you motivate
these top players

00:43:43.740 --> 00:43:46.500
to do the boring things in training?

00:43:46.700 --> 00:43:50.060
5 on 0, defense, things that players
understand very quickly

00:43:50.300 --> 00:43:54.820
and think they don’t need
to repeat 100 times.

00:43:55.820 --> 00:43:58.300
That is a problem,
because those who are the best,

00:43:58.391 --> 00:44:00.991
are the best because they
understand right away and apply it.

00:44:01.074 --> 00:44:02.834
Then you explain to them
that some things are repeated,

00:44:02.965 --> 00:44:04.645
not for them but for the others.

00:44:04.758 --> 00:44:08.798
But then, for the best ones,
you create a little trick.

00:44:10.060 --> 00:44:14.700
You tell them,
"Run the Five Down."

00:44:16.140 --> 00:44:19.420
When they start to do it, they realize
that such an offense doesn’t exist.

00:44:20.580 --> 00:44:23.140
Then I tell them, "Where are
you going, stop for a moment?"

00:44:24.020 --> 00:44:27.100
It’s a trick, but you have to
show them something too.

00:44:27.300 --> 00:44:32.918
Even the most focused players
make mistakes, and that’s the essence.

00:44:35.140 --> 00:44:38.740
The late Profa, as well as
all the best coaches,

00:44:39.740 --> 00:44:44.770
always said, and I’ll tell that
young coaches too,

00:44:44.996 --> 00:44:50.684
"Automatisms, when you have
an automaton, then that’s it."

00:44:52.620 --> 00:44:57.020
When we talk about offenses,
there are many in basketball.

00:44:57.260 --> 00:44:59.700
5 on 5 on half the court, screens, etc...

00:45:00.100 --> 00:45:04.740
My former player and great friend,
currently an outstanding coach,

00:45:05.060 --> 00:45:10.260
Šarūnas Jasikevičius,
when we met before the game

00:45:10.500 --> 00:45:14.100
against them here, he told me,
"Željko, what’s this?

00:45:14.340 --> 00:45:17.380
My assistants told me you stopped
running some offenses

00:45:17.620 --> 00:45:19.740
and now you’re playing simple things."

00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:24.740
Yes, I play simple things,
because I have players who can do that.

00:45:25.860 --> 00:45:29.540
Yes. -And the whole essence
is in that. Let’s simplify it,

00:45:29.740 --> 00:45:33.980
so that even those who don’t quite
understand can get it.

00:45:34.220 --> 00:45:37.005
That way, it will be easier for everyone.

00:45:37.384 --> 00:45:41.064
Let’s simplify everything,
so that everyone can do everything.

00:45:41.319 --> 00:45:44.287
And when the situation comes,
when we need something

00:45:44.451 --> 00:45:46.748
a little more complicated,
then we’ll choose these 5 or 7

00:45:47.020 --> 00:45:49.795
who are capable of doing it.
If, in that case, I put

00:45:49.876 --> 00:45:52.427
someone else on the court,
I can’t blame him,

00:45:52.529 --> 00:45:55.049
because it’s entirely my mistake
that he’s on the court at that moment.

00:45:55.173 --> 00:45:57.412
I know that when I talk to myself.

00:45:57.558 --> 00:46:00.943
And I don’t get angry at that player,
because he’s not at that level

00:46:01.069 --> 00:46:03.068
to be able to respond to that.

00:46:03.225 --> 00:46:08.896
When we were champions in 2017,
with Fenerbahçe I had a player,

00:46:09.300 --> 00:46:11.981
Ekpe Udoh, who was
the laziest at practice.

00:46:12.123 --> 00:46:16.323
Nobody liked him, not his teammates,
not the coaching staff, nobody.

00:46:16.616 --> 00:46:18.136
I had a conversation with him
and told him,

00:46:18.336 --> 00:46:20.696
"You’re bothering everyone, but I know
what you can give me in the game."

00:46:20.904 --> 00:46:23.144
He turned into a beast
during the game.

00:46:23.345 --> 00:46:25.958
He had incredible concentration.
It was enough to tell him,

00:46:26.180 --> 00:46:29.900
"In defense, we play this,"
or "In offense, we play that." A miracle.

00:46:30.140 --> 00:46:34.100
But at practice, he was lazy, lazy.
When the ball is loose and we’re

00:46:34.300 --> 00:46:36.580
playing 5 on 5, he’s a different person.

00:46:36.820 --> 00:46:40.648
Use that trait of his,
if it will lead you to your goal.

00:46:41.910 --> 00:46:44.148
I didn’t want to send him away.

00:46:44.280 --> 00:46:46.390
And Darryl Middleton,
at 40 years old,

00:46:46.540 --> 00:46:49.420
when I give them 3 on 0 fast break drills,
he was the first to dunk the ball.

00:46:49.660 --> 00:46:52.820
I always put him in the top three.
Then I tell them, "Wait a minute,

00:46:53.020 --> 00:46:55.100
you’re 18 years old, you’re 19,
and this man is 40 and still the first

00:46:55.340 --> 00:46:58.035
to dunk, the first to sprint,
and you can’t."

00:46:59.355 --> 00:47:05.598
Diversity is a miracle. -100%.
But this is your position, right?

00:47:06.500 --> 00:47:09.500
Players want to come to you,
they want trophies,

00:47:09.740 --> 00:47:13.100
they want to progress,
they want to feel what it is?

00:47:14.300 --> 00:47:18.500
Because you’ve launched yourself
to the very top and you’re protected.

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:20.620
You’ve earned all of that,
but you’re protected.

00:47:20.820 --> 00:47:23.060
Nothing can touch you,
up to a certain limit, of course,

00:47:23.260 --> 00:47:25.260
not the player, not the agent,
not the president,

00:47:25.460 --> 00:47:28.060
and not even the media will dare.

00:47:28.820 --> 00:47:32.860
Fans, of course, love blood,
tears, and sweat. -Yes.

00:47:35.180 --> 00:47:39.220
Try to put yourself in the position
of a new coach,

00:47:39.420 --> 00:47:42.540
like Mourinho at Manchester United.
The guy came from Sporting,

00:47:42.780 --> 00:47:47.660
where he defeated Benfica and Porto,
in three years, two titles. That’s top.

00:47:47.900 --> 00:47:51.860
He came there, things went badly,
and he said,

00:47:53.380 --> 00:47:57.300
"We are the worst
Manchester in history."

00:47:57.580 --> 00:48:00.980
That’s a massacre, you threw
the players under the bus,

00:48:01.180 --> 00:48:03.100
what kind of psychology is that?

00:48:03.380 --> 00:48:11.041
Can a coach today
rule sovereignly, like you?

00:48:14.875 --> 00:48:16.525
I'll explain one thing.

00:48:16.940 --> 00:48:20.220
In the last three years
players haven’t been coming

00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:22.700
because of me,
but because of Partizan.

00:48:22.980 --> 00:48:27.380
I always tell them to pay attention
to what kind of club they’re coming to.

00:48:27.660 --> 00:48:31.940
I know who I am.
When I talk to them, I am direct.

00:48:32.140 --> 00:48:35.820
I don't promise what I can't fulfill.
That's for sure.

00:48:36.060 --> 00:48:41.180
I tell them to watch Partizan
games and that atmosphere.

00:48:42.500 --> 00:48:45.500
Every player, during these four years,
as long as I've been in Partizan,

00:48:45.780 --> 00:48:48.100
is overjoyed to be playing
in Partizan,

00:48:48.340 --> 00:48:50.820
because we are the most
watched club in the world.

00:48:51.020 --> 00:48:54.900
Indeed, I think Parizan is specific.

00:48:55.100 --> 00:48:58.980
It was there before,
but it didn't have such players.

00:48:59.220 --> 00:49:03.220
We love black and whites and all that...
-Yes, but those were different times,

00:49:03.420 --> 00:49:05.540
it was the time of the pandemic.

00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:08.180
Partizan didn't participate
in the Euroleague.

00:49:08.380 --> 00:49:11.340
Now that's changed. When Dule was
a coach and many coaches before him...

00:49:11.540 --> 00:49:16.460
There were some strange
matches in the Euroleague.

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:22.451
Partizan fans are known for that.
It's not just my merit.

00:49:23.934 --> 00:49:26.443
Partizan fans also deserve it.

00:49:27.927 --> 00:49:32.961
But in answer to your question
I never thought

00:49:36.099 --> 00:49:42.680
that I am someone who is
irreplaceable and untouchable.

00:49:43.946 --> 00:49:51.758
I didn't even think of doing
something else than what I do.

00:49:52.303 --> 00:49:56.399
I am a coach,
in a club called now Partizan,

00:49:56.715 --> 00:49:59.360
and before that he was Fenerbahce,
then it was Panathinaikos.

00:49:59.495 --> 00:50:01.532
There are people
who have their own functions.

00:50:01.686 --> 00:50:03.726
It is known what the president
of the club does.

00:50:03.919 --> 00:50:06.266
The sports sector knows
what is being done.

00:50:06.500 --> 00:50:09.260
In the club management,
they also know what they are doing.

00:50:09.466 --> 00:50:13.026
It is known what the spokesman does,
he is in charge for public relations.

00:50:13.540 --> 00:50:16.860
I'm a coach. Of course,
experience that I have,

00:50:17.060 --> 00:50:20.540
will help all those people, if they
want. I always am ready to talk.

00:50:20.780 --> 00:50:28.057
I helped people who they are very
serious in their professions.

00:50:28.320 --> 00:50:34.229
Like the Giannakopoulos brothers
who did miracles with Panathinaikos.

00:50:35.100 --> 00:50:37.220
They are older than me.

00:50:37.500 --> 00:50:39.940
They considered me a son
and a member of the family.

00:50:40.820 --> 00:50:44.980
But they trusted me and asked to show,
explain what to do and make it work,

00:50:45.127 --> 00:50:47.847
but even then I wasn’t explicit
that it had to be that way.

00:50:47.969 --> 00:50:49.729
A coach must be dedicated
to his work.

00:50:52.080 --> 00:50:58.087
He can not interfere
in other matters.

00:50:59.703 --> 00:51:04.955
The coach shouldn’t be interested
whether he is attacked by journalists.

00:51:05.660 --> 00:51:09.060
Are they against him,
whatever the reason.

00:51:09.300 --> 00:51:16.900
Are it against him because of the fans?
Or because opposing club?

00:51:17.100 --> 00:51:22.300
Are they enviable, because we live
in the time in which jealousy reigns.

00:51:22.820 --> 00:51:25.740
I know all that and
I don't deal with it.

00:51:25.980 --> 00:51:30.500
I deal with myself,
my staff and players.

00:51:31.020 --> 00:51:33.420
And, of course,
fans are important to me,

00:51:33.660 --> 00:51:35.620
but without flattering them.

00:51:36.020 --> 00:51:41.100
Fans who support us
have the right to criticize.

00:51:41.380 --> 00:51:44.260
To say anything they
think is not good.

00:51:44.500 --> 00:51:49.860
That motivates us. But that's where
everything begins and ends.

00:51:50.180 --> 00:51:55.663
The limit of the coaching job
is not exceeded. -Bravo!

00:51:59.020 --> 00:52:02.940
Now we come to your relationship
with the players.

00:52:03.660 --> 00:52:10.100
What kind of relationship is that?
It is very wide and well known.

00:52:10.500 --> 00:52:14.220
You said your phone
always available.

00:52:14.620 --> 00:52:19.300
And from managers, directors,
but, primarily, your phone.

00:52:20.740 --> 00:52:24.500
I know coaches from the Premier
League. I won't say their names.

00:52:24.780 --> 00:52:31.485
To maintain their authority,
they show up for training on Friday,

00:52:32.098 --> 00:52:34.738
and the game is on Saturday.

00:52:38.739 --> 00:52:41.145
Or they watch pracitce
from the sidelines.

00:52:41.382 --> 00:52:44.902
I know coaches who say they
won the Premier League trophy.

00:52:45.660 --> 00:52:52.540
They told their players they can
knock twice a year in a season.

00:52:53.460 --> 00:52:58.860
Never on match day or before a match,
only twice a season.

00:52:59.100 --> 00:53:04.580
No more. And on the other hand,
you and I give everything we have.

00:53:05.260 --> 00:53:08.820
Contact with the players
is very important.

00:53:09.060 --> 00:53:11.500
As is individual and team conversation.

00:53:11.740 --> 00:53:16.940
I have never allowed myself to talk
to a player about another player.

00:53:17.220 --> 00:53:21.140
That is also a rule of life.
-Only in his presence.

00:53:22.660 --> 00:53:26.580
That is right. The most important
thing is to be honest.

00:53:26.780 --> 00:53:30.700
I have always been that.
I always say what I think.

00:53:31.020 --> 00:53:34.500
Sometimes someone
doesn't like it, but that is life.

00:53:35.180 --> 00:53:39.020
We have to be aware that everyone
has the right to say what they think.

00:53:39.260 --> 00:53:41.780
I'm like that with players.

00:53:42.180 --> 00:53:46.820
During the year, depending
on the situation and the season,

00:53:47.300 --> 00:53:49.700
if you talked to someone
at the beginning of the season,

00:53:49.900 --> 00:53:52.540
you have to remind them for that
conversation after a month,

00:53:52.740 --> 00:53:54.300
two or three days.

00:53:55.620 --> 00:53:58.620
Someone you had a problem
with at the beginning,

00:53:58.860 --> 00:54:03.740
you realize that you influenced
him to change in a positive way.

00:54:03.980 --> 00:54:08.740
You are proud of that.
It was always important to me

00:54:09.020 --> 00:54:11.660
when I end my cooperation
with the players

00:54:11.900 --> 00:54:15.540
we still maintain an excellent contact.

00:54:16.300 --> 00:54:20.500
In 34 or 35 years
that I have been a coach,

00:54:20.700 --> 00:54:23.620
there is not a single player,
that I have coached,

00:54:23.820 --> 00:54:29.020
who is not on good terms with me.
Now it was the game against Monaco.

00:54:29.220 --> 00:54:32.580
Calathes was a child when
he came to Panathinaikos.

00:54:32.820 --> 00:54:36.300
I told him that he would be the best
player in the Final Four in 2011.

00:54:36.540 --> 00:54:38.540
And he almost made it.
It was Diamantidis.

00:54:38.740 --> 00:54:42.060
And now it is 2025. Nick comes
to hug me before the game.

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:44.260
And Michael James,
who is the best scorer.

00:54:44.500 --> 00:54:46.740
I never coached him,
but he respects me.

00:54:46.940 --> 00:54:51.260
Shengelija and me, two days
before that we were together.

00:54:51.500 --> 00:54:56.020
I took them to a match for Dražen
Petrović. I remember that...

00:54:56.220 --> 00:54:58.620
We were playing against the Croatian
national team, and he called and said,

00:54:58.820 --> 00:55:01.180
"We are Dražen’s team,
we must not lose."

00:55:01.380 --> 00:55:03.660
I can’t forget that,
that was a friendly match.

00:55:03.900 --> 00:55:05.780
He showed me character then.

00:55:06.020 --> 00:55:08.580
I congratulated them and gathered them.
Musa and that team I led...

00:55:08.820 --> 00:55:10.700
And we won then.

00:55:10.900 --> 00:55:15.260
It doesn’t matter! We won, because
they said "This is Dražen’s team!"

00:55:15.460 --> 00:55:17.020
"You know who Dražen was?"

00:55:17.260 --> 00:55:23.500
The respect you have makes
you satisfied and happy.

00:55:23.780 --> 00:55:27.860
When people respect you...
Of course, after a year,

00:55:28.100 --> 00:55:32.140
or when you work with someone
for a longer period of time,

00:55:32.380 --> 00:55:34.900
some difficult situations arise,
but we are human.

00:55:35.140 --> 00:55:37.300
We have to tell each other
what we think.

00:55:37.540 --> 00:55:39.340
And come out of that situation
even stronger,

00:55:39.540 --> 00:55:41.340
because it is good
for you and for me.

00:55:41.580 --> 00:55:47.560
But the most important is the team.
-Excellent, I agree with that.

00:55:48.552 --> 00:55:50.820
It is known that in the past...

00:55:51.060 --> 00:55:53.380
The coach was given authority
based on position.

00:55:53.580 --> 00:55:57.740
You think that in these times,
I am going back to that...

00:55:57.940 --> 00:56:00.540
I told you about this during lunch...

00:56:00.740 --> 00:56:07.312
You and Jokić come to Barcelona now.
That is the reality.

00:56:08.180 --> 00:56:14.062
You and Jokić come to Barcelona now.
The authority is with him.

00:56:16.180 --> 00:56:18.820
Before, you weren't allowed
to say anything to Jokić,

00:56:19.060 --> 00:56:23.900
because he was the boss, but
that authority has changed a bit.

00:56:24.300 --> 00:56:30.820
Coaches are expected to have
absolute authority, but they don't.

00:56:31.140 --> 00:56:33.460
Sport is just a reflection of life.

00:56:33.700 --> 00:56:36.681
Not even a kindergarten
teacher has authority.

00:56:36.901 --> 00:56:40.025
Neither a school teacher,
nor a police officer,

00:56:40.251 --> 00:56:43.251
and even a parent has a different
kind of authority today

00:56:43.490 --> 00:56:46.127
than in our time. -That's right.

00:56:48.420 --> 00:56:52.460
Does this new mentality bother you?

00:56:53.820 --> 00:56:56.420
"I don't care, we're partners."

00:56:57.860 --> 00:57:00.620
The generation gap is something
very important.

00:57:00.900 --> 00:57:03.180
I'm going back to where I started.

00:57:03.420 --> 00:57:05.740
These were people
with whom it was easy.

00:57:05.940 --> 00:57:10.820
Now I coach the sons of the players
that I used to coach.

00:57:14.780 --> 00:57:18.180
Maybe I'll wait for a grandchild...

00:57:18.940 --> 00:57:21.020
And continue working
a few more years?

00:57:21.220 --> 00:57:23.500
I'm trying to get down to their level.

00:57:23.740 --> 00:57:29.860
What young people are going
through now, I must to understand.

00:57:31.420 --> 00:57:36.980
Of course, the life is beautiful.

00:57:37.860 --> 00:57:40.300
When someone laughs,

00:57:40.500 --> 00:57:43.540
the pleasure that laughter brings
to people is something important.

00:57:43.780 --> 00:57:48.580
I know I'm strict on the court, but
I'm completely different off the court.

00:57:49.300 --> 00:57:52.500
I try to talk to these young people
about topics

00:57:52.740 --> 00:57:59.180
that I believe are interesting to them.
Sometimes I succeed, sometimes I don't.

00:57:59.380 --> 00:58:03.140
You have to knock on their door
to get them to open it.

00:58:03.380 --> 00:58:06.740
When they open their door, it's easier.
Sometimes they keep it closed.

00:58:07.020 --> 00:58:11.140
Maybe they think the coach
has authority,

00:58:11.340 --> 00:58:15.380
how can I deal with him? When they
see that, and some time passes...

00:58:15.620 --> 00:58:19.340
I love those dinners and lunches,
and when one of us,

00:58:19.620 --> 00:58:22.940
but I am always late,
then I pay for the first dinner.

00:58:23.180 --> 00:58:28.140
We get together, we drink
and we tell human stories.

00:58:28.380 --> 00:58:31.460
So that they can know
that I'm one of them.

00:58:31.660 --> 00:58:36.580
That's right. We're a team,
there's no "me" and "you".

00:58:36.820 --> 00:58:40.300
We'll always be a team. The sooner
you explain, the easier it gets.

00:58:40.580 --> 00:58:45.794
Of course, that generation gap
exists and will always exist.

00:58:46.012 --> 00:58:49.052
You're absolutely right,
times have changed.

00:58:49.620 --> 00:58:53.820
We used to not have many
opportunities to choose

00:58:54.060 --> 00:58:56.380
what we're going to do in life.

00:58:56.620 --> 00:59:01.140
But the best players show
that even in this time.

00:59:01.420 --> 00:59:05.060
Dedication is by far
the most important thing.

00:59:05.380 --> 00:59:09.780
That's what makes the difference
between equals. -Exactly.

00:59:10.820 --> 00:59:13.460
That would be all in this
special edition

00:59:13.740 --> 00:59:16.740
"Unsuccess of the champion
with Slaven Bilić".

00:59:17.020 --> 00:59:19.740
Watch the second part of the interview
with Željko Obradović

00:59:19.980 --> 00:59:25.100
on Arena Sport 1,
March 3rd at 8 p.m.

00:59:25.620 --> 00:59:28.900
When you watch those
short clips about you,

00:59:29.340 --> 00:59:32.500
you sometimes surprise yourself.

00:59:32.700 --> 00:59:36.020
You say. "What is this?"
"Aleksa, Aleksa!"

00:59:36.500 --> 00:59:39.580
Do you want me to break
the board on your head?

00:59:39.860 --> 00:59:42.100
I was trying to explain
to the players,

00:59:42.380 --> 00:59:44.700
while I am talking to you,
you interest me.

00:59:44.940 --> 00:59:47.500
I'm not thinking about whether
I'll be fired tomorrow.

00:59:47.700 --> 00:59:49.660
At Partizan, of course.

00:59:50.020 --> 00:59:51.900
I have to tell you this...

00:59:52.140 --> 00:59:55.820
If you don't want to do coaching,
this job is going well for you.

00:59:56.020 --> 00:59:58.260
You're an encyclopedia...

00:59:58.500 --> 01:00:01.660
Željko, I have to say
something in the end.

01:00:03.480 --> 01:00:04.916
You're really unique!

